# Performance

## Trust the React Compiler

Do not add `React.memo`, `useMemo`, or `useCallback`. The compiler (enabled in `next.config.ts`) handles memoization automatically. Manual wrappers add overhead and can conflict.

## Server Components first

Keep components as Server Components by default. Only add `"use client"` when the file genuinely needs hooks, event handlers, or browser APIs. Push the client boundary as deep into the tree as possible so the server can stream more HTML.

## Dynamic imports for heavy libraries

Use `next/dynamic` with `ssr: false` for components that depend on large browser-only packages: maplibre-gl, deck.gl, ag-grid, monaco-editor, recharts, onnxruntime-web, tensorflow.js.

## Zustand selectors

Always select individual fields — never call a store hook without a selector. A bare `useMapStore()` re-renders on every store change.

## React Query cache tuning

Set `staleTime` appropriate to the data's volatility. The global default is in `lib/query/provider.tsx`; override per-query when needed. Avoid redundant refetches by using `initialData` or `placeholderData` from the cache.

## `startTransition` for expensive updates

Wrap state updates that trigger heavy re-renders (filtering large datasets, switching visualization modes) in `startTransition` so they don't block user input.

```ts
import { startTransition } from "react";

startTransition(() => {
  setFilteredFeatures(applyFilter(allFeatures, query));
});
```

## CSS over JS

Prefer Tailwind classes for animations, transitions, and layout shifts. Avoid JS-driven animations unless the animation depends on runtime values that CSS cannot express.
